Problem statement
The problem states to use a large language model (LLM), or language learning model as I interpret it to track popular LLM YouTube channels. The aim of this task is to automate and provide livestream tracking and analysis of popular YouTube channels focusing on LLM-related topics.

Methodology
I chose Claude (a substitute of OpenClaw) to automate tracking of the popular YouTube channels focusing on LLMs. This agentic coding tool is selected for its ability to read my codebase, runs commands, and automates development tasks, which are applicable to the nature of this task. 
Due to time constraint, I employed random sampling technique by asking the model to select 9 popular YouTube channels focusing on LLM. I also manually cross-checked YouTube channels scrapped by Claude to ensure reliability of the channels such as hosts content

The procedures are as the following:
1.	I defined Claude into Cowork mode, given the task aims to automate tracking and analysis of LLM Landscape on YouTube 
2.	I created a folder on Cowork named LLM YouTube tracker. Given this task is an exercise, I set the basic Sonnet 4.6 language model instead of Opus 4.6 model that requires subscription However, in the future if the company is willing to provide sponsorship, Opus 4.6 model will be prioritised for its ability to maximize search effort / amount
3.	I put in the instructions of this exercise as prompts to the chatbot and let the model run, extract data, and compile data into tables that categorizes videos covering topics, hosts, and thematic overlaps
4.	To execute live solution, I asked Claude to set up a scheduled task that runs weekly, searches for new videos from all 7 channels, and refreshes the artifact automatically


Evaluation Dataset
Overall the table presents clearly the topics, hosts, and thematic overlaps of the 7 popular YouTube channels focusing on LLM. The table color-coded the topics, themes, and audience level, offering clear visual presentations that allow data analyst to quickly spot 
Occasionally the social media metrics (eg, number of subscribers) provided by the model are inaccurate as I manually cross check on YouTube. This mismatch in data could be due to the basic Sonnet 4.6 model deployed for this exercise. 

Experimental Results
What was requested: A live, auto-updating tracker of popular LLM YouTube channels — with a video table, theme overlap map, and transcript-derived insights per video.
What was delivered:
The tracker artifact in my sidebar covers 7 channels (Karpathy, Lex Fridman, Dwarkesh, Yannic Kilcher, AI Explained, IBM Technology, Matt Wolfe) across 3 tabs — channel profiles, a filterable video table with 19 rows, and a theme overlap matrix. A weekly scheduled task runs every Monday at 9am and rebuilds the table with fresh search results, pushing updates back into the artifact automatically.
Where it worked well:
The channel profiles, topic classification, and theme overlap map came together cleanly. The Creator's Take column is grounded — Karpathy's quotes about hallucinations, RLVR, and vibe coding came from his actual blog post and transcripts; Lex Fridman #490 had a full official transcript; the Dwarkesh × Karpathy episode had detailed show notes with verbatim quotes; the LLM Neuroanatomy row traces back to the original technical paper.
Limitations of Claude-Powered Tracking and Mapping of the LLM Landscape on YouTube Channels
Three things were blocked at the network level: YouTube direct access (so no scraping captions), PyPI (so youtube-transcript-api couldn't be installed), and most third-party transcript mirror sites (ytscribe, tactiq, shortform, etc.). This meant authentic caption-level transcription — word-for-word from the audio — wasn't achievable in this environment. The Creator's Take column is the closest viable substitute: official transcripts where they exist, high-fidelity creator blog posts and verbatim quotes elsewhere.
To resolve the access issue, I first enabled network access on Claude settings, then opened Chrome on my laptop, installed Claude chrome extension and signed into my YouTube account. To achieve authentic caption-level transcripts folded in, the cleanest path would be to run youtube-transcript-api locally outside the sandbox. Alternatively, use a YouTube Data API key with caption access, and feed the output back in as a file.
